<HEADLINE>
<P>
FORD TIGHTENS ITS POLICY ON SMOKING 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
DEARBORN, Mich. 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Ford Motor Co. on Friday announced new restrictions on smoking in its U.S. 
facilities. 
</P>
<P>
Effective June 1, smoking will be prohibited in conference rooms, training 
rooms, classrooms and auditoriums. The ban will be expanded Jan. 1, 1990, to 
include all enclosed offices and open office areas, the No. 2 auto maker said 
in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
The restrictions will not apply to smoking in open factory and garage areas 
within certain guidelines, the statement said. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
'Bold Step' 
</P>
<P>
Ford also said it would expand services and programs for both salaried and 
hourly employees interested in quitting smoking. 
</P>
<P>
Ford previously had designated smoking and non-smoking areas in cafeterias 
while smoking was prohibited in some work areas because of safety, Ford 
spokesman Dick Routh said. 
</P>
<P>
"It's a bold step forward but reflects a growing feeling among employees that 
they want a healthier work environment," Routh said. 
</P>
