<HEADLINE>
<P>
REVIEWS OF TODAY'S AFI FILM FEST 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MICHAEL WILMINGTON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Following are capsule reviews of today's screenings in the American Film 
Institute Los Angeles International Film Festival at the Cineplex Odeon Century 
Plaza Cinemas: 
</P>
<P>
'Illusory Thoughts' and 'The Money Juggler' 
</P>
<P>
United States, 1988, 131 minutes 
</P>
<P>
8:45 p.m. 
</P>
<P>
 One good, one not-so. The weaker entry, "Illusory Thoughts," shows 
writer-director-star Patrick Chu, a Hong Kong-born choreographer, as the 
pensive Nam, wandering around Manhattan, ruminating ruefully on how ephemeral 
life is, while various women fight over him. Leo Rubinfein's "The Money 
Juggler" is a well-acted, well-shot, intelligent adaptation of a Louis 
Auchincloss short story.MICHAEL WILMINGTON 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Motion Picture Review 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
