<HEADLINE>
<P>
JOHNSON WELCOME AT '92 OLYMPICS, SAMARANCH SAYS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
BARCELONA, Spain 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Ben Johnson would be welcome to compete in the 1992 Olympics even though he was 
caught using steroids at the Games in Seoul last summer, the head of the 
International Olympic Committee said Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
IOC President Juan Antonio Samaranch said Johnson must be treated like any 
other athlete, despite being involved in the biggest drug scandal in Olympic 
history. 
</P>
<P>
"Why not?" Samaranch said when asked if he would like to see Johnson competing 
for a gold medal again. "Johnson was treated like any other athlete in Seoul 
when we suspended him. Now, we have to do the same. . . . He must not get more 
sanctions because he is Johnson. This is not fair." 
</P>
<P>
Samaranch spoke as the Olympic committee's executive board prepared to open 
four days of meetings in this Spanish coastal city, where the 1992 Games will 
be held. 
</P>
</TEXT>
