<LENGTH>
<P>
337 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
JOHNSON'S THERAPIST TESTIFIES ON STEROID USE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
TORONTO 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Ben Johnson's physiotherapist admitted today that he administered what he 
believed were muscle-building steroids to Canadian athletes but said he never 
discussed the topic with Johnson, his teammates or the doctor who supplied the 
banned drugs. 
</P>
<P>
Waldemar Matuszewski, a surprise witness at the federal inquiry into drug use 
in amateur sport, said he assumed the chemicals he administered were steroids 
but never confirmed that with Dr. Jamie Astaphan, Johnson's physician. 
</P>
<P>
"I never asked, but I knew," Matuszewski told the inquiry. "Only steroids would 
build muscles like that." 
</P>
<P>
Speaking with a heavy Polish accent, the Warsaw-born Matuszewski, 42, gave a 
confusing story in which he denied allegations made in earlier testimony that 
he was part of widespread cheating by Johnson and his Canadian teammates. 
</P>
<P>
Matuszewski also denied that he had injected steroids into Italy's top 
sprinter, Pierfrancesco Pavoni, in Toronto in the fall of 1987. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
Testimony Disputed 
</P>
<P>
Pavoni has also described testimony by retired Canadian sprinter Mike 
Sokolowski as "absolutely false." 
</P>
<P>
Sokolowski admitted using steroids and said he saw Matuszewski give Pavoni an 
injection. 
</P>
<P>
Inquiry spokesmen said last week that Peter Dajia, a shot putter once kicked 
off Canada's Commonwealth Games team for failing a drug test, would be the 
first witness when the inquiry resumed after a weeklong break. 
</P>
<P>
Also expected to testify was hurdler Mark McKoy, one of Johnson's closest 
friends who left the Seoul Olympics last year after the star sprinter tested 
positive for the anabolic steroid stanozolol and was suspended from 
international competition for two years. 
</P>
<P>
The commission does not adhere to a rigid hearing schedule, but spokeswoman 
Barbara Fox said the current plans are for three weeks of testimony from 
athletes, doctors and drug companies before the next recess. 
</P>
<P>
Dajia, 25, who attended the University of Texas, tested positive for steroids 
at the trials for the 1986 Commonwealth Games and was suspended from the 
Canadian team. 
</P>
</TEXT>
